1) $TSLA will need to spend ~$230m on Service Centers (SC) in China in 2020 (15% of 2019 capex). While $TSLA's fleet is 2.2K vehicles/SC globally, in China it's a whopping 3.1K/SC. The Chinese--unlike cultist US owners--won't tolerate long waits. They protest when mistreated.

2) $TSLA only has 29 SCs in China (408 globally), which by 2019 end should equate to 3.1K Teslas/SC in China (40% > global avg). The SCs alone should cost ~$7m each & $TSLA is planning to more than double them to 63 "in the coming months" (Reuters).

3) My estimate of $230m is conservative, assuming that only 1/2 of the additions are made in the 3 main cities (probably a higher % needed, as they have more wealthy $TSLA owners). Showroom openings planned at 102, so SG&A should see at least a $30-$50m spike from rent in 2020.

4) But even if $TSLA doles out $230m for the extra 34 SCs planned for China, the total fleet/SC will still be a high 2.8K/SC (30% > global avg). There's also a question of how many spare parts $TSLA can afford to hold at all of its SCs in China (expect higher inventory).

5) I have a feeling that, as $TSLA's fleet grows in China, its brand value deteriorates. $TSLA can't afford to pay for the infrastructure needed to service its Chinese customers. And Chinese customers will take Tesla to task for any short-comings, unlike most in the US.$TSLAQ

1/ The best thing about writing is not what I write, but what I learn from others. Case in point: the recent collaboration with @orthereaboot on $tsla's propensity to charge to goodwill expenses that belong in warranty.

2/ We showed that $tsla engages in such a practice, that it may well be pervasive, & that it artificially inflates Gross Profit and Net Income. It's not a sexy topic. It takes time & patience to work through the numbers to see how it works.

3/ But considering $tsla's Q3 profit, net of FX adjustments, was only about $30 million, it's entirely plausible that fudging on classification of warranty expenses accounted for all of that, and more.

4/ Did our critics take shots at our analysis? Naturally. Were some of those shots valid? Perhaps a bit. The most popular theme was that we can't prove that even though the service records say "goodwill" (SG&A) $tsla didn't actually classify the expense as warranty (COGS).

5/ A more solid line of criticism agreed that while the misclassification is occurring, the warranty expenses wrongly classified as goodwill are hitting the "Services & Other" category which, though it should be a big source of profit, is persistently a big loss for $tsla.

6/ Such a misclassification would not distort Gross Profit (because "Services & other" is part of COGS rather than SG&A) but would artificially inflate Net Income by allowing $tsla to set an artificially low warranty reserve.

2/ Following 31% q/q deliveries decline in Q1 (as US M3 backlog was exhausted and Europe deliveries had not started en masse), $TSLA managed to grow deliveries sequentially from Q1’s low base throughout the rest of FY2019.

3/ Q4 will follow Q2 and Q3 in setting new deliveries records, this time at >110k, driven by geographic expansion, release of RHD M3 and expiration of various tax incentives (NL, US FIT).However, $TSLA will barely hit the lower end of its delivery guidance of 360-400k in FY2019

4/ In Q4 2018 deliveries report $TSLA said they ended FY2018 with a 350k deliveries run-rate, and FY2019 will end with ~365k deliveries. Either production didn’t improve at all, or $TSLA manufactured to demand. (h/t @Badger24)Declining ASPs suggest demand issue is more likely.

5/ In Q3 2019, $TSLA auto revenue declined q/q and ~12% y/y. Q4 auto revenue may beat Q3 q/q comp depending on mix, but will be down y/y and mark first LTM revenue decline.Revenue is already declining despite record deliveries, as mix (and thus ASPs) continue to deteriorate.

8/ $TSLA will need to rush both MY and CT to market, having realized M3 demand will not sustain the growth without new geographies left to expand to.Notably cumulative M3 deliveries post-Q4 will barely be at the “420k reservations” number, despite a $1,000 deposit at the time.

9/ MY and CT deliveries are unlikely to start in time to contribute much to 1H 2020 with $TSLA having guided for MY deliveries starting in late 2020 (and Deutsche expecting early 2020 start) and CT in late 2021. $TSLA famously doesn’t tend to hit their estimated timelines.

10/ The 250k CT “deposits” were $100/each, 90% below M3 where most reservations never translated to sales. With no 300k update from Musk, it’s unlikely CT has gotten there.Notably $TSLA never put out a MY reservations number, saying it's not "relevant". Make of it what you will

11/ $TSLA will need >100k of production from Shanghai in FY2020 to have a shot at their consensus revenue estimates, but that assumes demand for >100k incremental sales, even before looking at profitability, at a time when ASPs seemingly remain the only lever to increase demand.

12/ Consensus estimates call for $5.07 of EPS in FY2020E and $10.89 in FY2021E. $TSLA’s mix is not improving (i.e. ASP will only decrease further), meaning they must rely on further efficiencies and cost cuts to remain margin neutral – and consensus calls for a profitable year.

13/ In addition, $TSLA need to sell enough vehicles from China to generate $300mm of annual tax revenue to avoid the risk of giving the factory back to the Chinese govt, which helped put it up in record time. That will add pressure to move metal, even at lower ASPs.

15/ $TSLA has never had a profitable (or cash flow positive) year, even when they were the only EV option for many consumers, and thus held strong pricing power. That advantage is disappearing with more and more EVs coming to market, putting more pressure on the company.

16/ Each year forward will bring in new and tougher competition from other OEMs, which will spread demand for EVs around a larger pool, mean less demand for regulatory credits, and decrease the impact of any incremental EV tax incentives for $TSLA.
